File: rust/lichen-ipv6/src/lib.rs:538-550

The from_bytes() function expects:
```rust
// After type/code/checksum: 4 reserved + 16 target
if buf.len() < 20 {
    return Err(TooShort::new(20, buf.len()).into());
}
let mut target = [0u8; 16];
target.copy_from_slice(&buf[4..20]);
```

But looking at how it's called in handle_icmpv6:
```rust
let body = &icmpv6_payload[ICMPV6_HEADER_LEN..];  // Skip type/code/checksum (4 bytes)
// ...
let ns = NeighborSolicitation::from_bytes(body)?;
```

So 'body' already has type/code/checksum stripped. The NS format after those 4 bytes is:
- 4 bytes reserved
- 16 bytes target address

This means buf[4..20] is correct (4 reserved + 16 target starting at offset 4).

Wait, this is actually correct. The comment says 'After type/code/checksum: 4 reserved + 16 target', and the function receives data that already has type/code/checksum stripped.

Let me re-verify... Actually this is correct. Canceling this bead.
